# Assignment 3 - Exploratory data analysis of the Titanic dataset

The RMS Titanic was a British passenger liner that sank in the North Atlantic Ocean in the early morning hours of 15 April 1912, after it collided with an iceberg during its maiden voyage from Southampton to New York City. There were an estimated 2,224 passengers and crew aboard the ship, and more than 1,500 died, making it one of the deadliest commercial peacetime maritime disasters in modern history. The RMS Titanic was the largest ship afloat at the time it entered service and was the second of three Olympic-class ocean liners operated by the White Star Line. The Titanic was built by the Harland and Wolff shipyard in Belfast. Thomas Andrews, her architect, died in the disaster.

source: wikipedia.org

Description of the titanic dataset:¶

survived - Survival (0 = No; 1 = Yes)
plass - Passenger Class (1 = 1st; 2 = 2nd; 3 = 3rd)
sex - Gender
age - Age
sibsp - Number of Siblings/Spouses Aboard
parch - Number of Parents/Children Aboard
fare - Passenger fare
embarked - Port of Embarkation (C = Cherbourg; Q = Queenstown; S = Southampton)
class - Class as string
who - Type of person (child, man, woman)
adult_male - Passenger is an adult male
deck - Deck of passenger's accomodation
embark_town - Port of Embarkation as string
alive - Boolean
alone - Person travelled alone

* survived --> the values of this variable are not exactly numerical so I wouldn't use int64. I would use category (instead of object) because the variable has limited range of values (it can only be 0 or 1), so making processing faster by assigning this variable as category i beneficial. * pclass --> category, for same reasons as "survived". * age --> Age can be float but upon observation I didn't see any data gathered as a float within this variable (as expected). So it can simply be stored as int64. * embarked --> If the only entries are Cherbourg, Queenstown and Southampton maybe storing these as category would be better but it would not cause a problem by being object type of data either. * who and embark_town --> same as "embarked". * alive --> can be category to make processing faster or if the entries are changed (from yes to True and no to False) can also be boolean.

But I didn't exactly understand why does deck has 203 entries. I considered that maybe this is the actual number of total entries, but all the other variables that have 891 entries having the same number of missing values seemed not so possible...

## 4. Who did survive?

For each question below, create a chart in the axes above that helps you answer the questions. It is ok to stick to the plots implemented in seaborn. Some plots, like stacked bar charts, require more work.

Who had the highest chance of survival: men, women, or children? Hint: You can add another dimension to you `displot` or `countplot` by coloring bars with 'hue=column_name'.

sns.set_style("whitegrid")

ax = sns.countplot(x='survived', hue=titanic["who"], data=titanic, palette="flare")

ax.set_title('Survival Rates of Different Type of Passengers')

ax.legend(title="Type of Person", labels=["Man", "Woman", "Child"])

sns.despine();

Looking at the plot it seems like among the three type of passengers, only in the case of women the number of survivors are exceeding the number of non-survivors. Thus, I would say women had the highest chance of survival.

Did age have an influence? Compare the age of people who survived and those who did not. Is your observation consistent for all three types of people (men, women, children)?
In [11]:
#A plot that shows probability density of survival depending on age, without looking at the gender.
g = sns.FacetGrid(titanic, hue = "survived", height = 5, xlim = (0, 100), palette="flare").map(sns.kdeplot, "age", fill = True).add_legend()
g.fig.suptitle("Probabilities of Surviving and Not Surviving Depending on Age");

When probability densities of surviving and not surviving compared, there are three age groups standing out that seemingly has a disposition towards one of the two consequences. Roughly the age group of 0-10 had a higher chance of surviving, the age group of 18-32 had a higher chance of not surviving, and lastly the age group of 60-80 had also a higher chance of not surviving.

When analyzing the same data regarding the type of passengers we can no longer see the same age groups with similar dispositions. Here we can say men who were roughly aged between 30 to 55 had a higher chance of surviving whereas men aged between 55 and over had a lower chance of surviving. Chance of surviving for women seems to be mostly fluctiating. And for children we can confidently say with incresing age the chances of survival is decreasing.

Did people on all decks have the same survival rate?

The probabilities of survival and death can be computed as follows. We count the total number of people in each group (pandas.Series.value_counts) and divide by the total number of passengers:

In [13]:
titanic['alive'].value_counts() / len(titanic)
Out[13]:
no     0.616162
yes    0.383838
Name: alive, dtype: float64

We see that the total survival rate was 38%.

To do the same for each deck, we first to handle NaN-values in the deck entries. We add a new column, that has a categorical entry "None" for all passengers with an unspecified deck entry:

In [14]:
titanic['deck_all'] = titanic['deck'].cat.add_categories("None").fillna("None")
Now compute the survival rates per deck and plot the resulting series using, for example, [`seaborn.barplot`](https://seaborn.pydata.org/generated/seaborn.barplot.html).

Hints:

  • Pandas allows you to filter data. titanic[ titanic['age'] > 10 ] returns a series of all passengers that are older than 10 years. This can be used to filter only people that survived.
  • You can divide a series by a series elementwise. titanic['fare'] / titanic['age'] computes for each passanger the fraction fare divided by age (i.e. ticket price per year they lived - which is nonesense, but computable).
In [15]:
sns.set_style("whitegrid")

survivors = titanic[titanic["survived"] == 1]
surv_rates = (survivors["deck"].value_counts() / titanic["deck"].value_counts()).sort_index()

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.barplot(x=surv_rates.index, y=surv_rates.values, palette='flare')
plt.title('Survival Rates of Passengers Depending on Deck')
plt.xlabel('Deck')
plt.ylabel('Survival Rate')
plt.show()
## 5. Fake news?

You talk to a friend about the titanic dataset and he/she says:

It's so unfair. Only elderly people could afford First Class tickets and have a good trip on the Titanic.

Briefly discuss this statement. Write approximately 10-15 lines.

Hint:

  • Explanation of Discuss: Essentially this is a written debate where you are using your skill at reasoning, backed up by carefully selected evidence to make a case for and against an argument, or point out the advantages and disadvantages of a given context. Remember to arrive at a conclusion. source (not necessary to read): Essay terms explained by University of Leicester

Answer:¶

Although it seems plauisible to think that older people posses greater financial opportunities, upon observation of below graphs one cannot simply say only the elderly people could affors first class tickets and thus, had a good trip on the titanic. What we can say is that the people who booked first class tickets has a lot more varied when it comes to their ages. Another point is that the majority of people who booked first class tickets are relatively older when compared to other ticket classes, but it is hard to say whether this difference is a significant one. Because as can be seen from the boxplot, the interquartile range is rougly between 25 and 50 with a median of 38 (estimated). Now it is up to my friend whether he/she would consider someone who is 38 is elderly, but I don't. All in all, instead of saying "Only elderly people could afford First Class tickets and have a good trip on the Titanic" maybe one can say "The age range of the majority of people who booked first class tickets are lower than the age range of than those who booked second class tickets. Whereas the age range of the majority of people who booked first class tickets is more evenly distributed, resembling more of an platykurtic distribution.". In this case we can think about other possible factors that may have been played a role in the selection of ticket classes. Maybe it is about the limited amount of first class tickets, maybe a variety of age groups bougth these tickets and when there are only second or third class tickets left elderly people hesitated because they thought it would not be as comfortable for them to cruise in other classes whereas young people did not hesitate about anything. In conclusion, I disagree with the idea of only the elderly people could afford first class tickets.
